{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17471731","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17471731"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T21:50:54+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T21:50:54+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"586"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"586","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/586"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.02,0.87,0.03,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"586"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54550"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"586","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/586"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"586"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40059"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"128"},{"type":"tags","id":"1036"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1114"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2270"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2288"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42102"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44030"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54550","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/54550"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 17-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a one-day history of chest pain that worsens on deep inspiration. The pain does not radiate and is not associated with shortness of breath. She reports having a runny nose, dry cough, and headache for the past three days, which she attributed to a mild cold. She has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears generally well. Her pulse rate is 82/min, blood pressure 110/74 mmHg, respiratory rate 18/min, SpO2 99% on room air, and temperature 38.1\u00b0C. On auscultation of the chest, a squeaking sound is heard left of the sternal border.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn ECG is performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Pleurisy","Pulmonary embolism","Pericarditis","Costochondritis","Pneumonia"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe most likely diagnosis in this case is \u003Cstrong\u003Epericarditis\u003C/strong\u003E. The clinical presentation strongly supports this diagnosis: pleuritic chest pain, fever, recent history suggestive of a viral upper respiratory tract infection, and auscultation revealing a pericardial friction rub (described as a squeaking sound). The ECG changes, showing diffuse ST elevation with concave upwards morphology, are characteristic of acute pericarditis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPleurisy\u003C/strong\u003E, or inflammation of the pleura, can cause similar chest pain that worsens with respiration. However, pleurisy would not account for the ECG changes seen in this patient, nor would it typically present with a friction rub on auscultation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPulmonary embolism\u003C/strong\u003E is an important differential to consider in any patient with acute chest pain. However, this patient\u0027s normal heart rate, oxygen saturation, and respiratory rate make this diagnosis less likely. While PE can occasionally cause ST elevation on ECG, it more commonly presents with sinus tachycardia or signs of right heart strain.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECostochondritis\u003C/strong\u003E, a musculoskeletal cause of chest pain, could explain the patient\u0027s chest discomfort but would not account for her fever, friction rub, or ECG findings. Typically, costochondritis would present with reproducible tenderness over the affected costochondral joints.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPneumonia\u003C/strong\u003E should be considered given the fever and recent upper respiratory symptoms. However, pneumonia would not explain the ECG findings, and the absence of respiratory symptoms or abnormal lung sounds (apart from the friction rub) makes this diagnosis less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPericarditis is most commonly caused by viral infections, with 80-90% of cases attributed to viruses such as coxsackieviruses, echoviruses, cytomegalovirus, and herpes viruses. Treatment typically involves NSAIDs and colchicine, with steroids reserved for refractory cases or when first-line treatments are contraindicated. In uncomplicated cases like this one, pericardial drainage or pericardiotomy is not typically required.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Pleuritic chest pain and a friction rub after a recent viral infection in an otherwise fit and healthy individual is highly suggestive of pericarditis.","ECG changes in pericarditis typically show diffuse ST elevation with PR depression.","Pericarditis is most commonly caused by viral infections, particularly coxsackieviruses, echoviruses, cytomegalovirus, and herpes viruses."],"references":["http://www.uptodate.com/contents/clinical-presentation-and-diagnostic-evaluation-of-acute-pericarditis","Imazio M, Gaita F, LeWinter M. Evaluation and Treatment of Pericarditis: A Systematic Review. JAMA. 2015 Oct 13;314(14):1498-506. doi: 10.1001/jama.2015.12763. Erratum in: JAMA. 2015 Nov 10;314(18):1978. Erratum in: JAMA. 2016 Jan 5;315(1):90."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40059"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"586"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"17553"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"17553","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/17553"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/0456485c-e366-4ac7-aaba-af8056cc3922.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/0456485c-e366-4ac7-aaba-af8056cc3922.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":800,"height":479}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40059","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/40059"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-07T11:10:24+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-07T11:12:15+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"586"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54550"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"descript